{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01CXeWKuB54SF71kScNc4a29","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good. `ccode_config::load()` is cheap (just reads a TOML file). It's fine to call it in the CLI.\n\nNow let me plan the complete implementation:\n\n### Changes needed:\n\n1. **`crates/cli/Cargo.toml`**: Add `ccode-config = { path = \"../config\" }`\n\n2. **`crates/config/src/schema.rs`**: Add `TuiConfig` and `tui` field to `Config`\n\n3. **`crates/cli/src/cmd/tui.rs`**: Major changes\n   - Add necessary imports for colors and text styling\n   - Create a `ColorSupport` enum to detect terminal capabilities\n   - Build a `Theme` struct to hold styled elements\n   - Integrate theme into `AppState`\n   - Update the `run()` function to detect color support and apply fallbacks\n   - Refactor all render functions to use themed styles\n   - Add test coverage\n\nNow I'm implementing the color detection and theming system...\n\nDefining color support detection...\n\nBuilding the theme structure... Continuing with the color definitions for the high-contrast theme and other UI states... Defining the no-color theme variant...\n\nNow I need to add a `theme` field to `AppState` and implement a custom `Default` since `Theme` doesn't derive it automatically.\n\nI'm thinking through the initialization order: `AppState` gets created before the config loads, so I'll start with an environment-based default theme, then apply the configured theme name afterward if one exists in the config file. Now I'm handling the theme override from the config file—if a theme name is specified, I'll rebuild the theme with that preference and the detected color support. Then I'm refactoring the conversation rendering to use styled spans instead of plain text, applying the theme's user and assistant line styles to each entry.\n\nFor the assistant messages, I'm splitting multi-line text so the first line gets the \"Assistant:\" prefix while subsequent lines are indented for readability, and I need to handle the edge case where text ends with a newline.\n\nNow I'm realizing there's a lifetime issue—the function returns `Vec<Line<'static>>` but I'm working with string references. Since `format!()` produces owned `String` values, those can be converted to the `'static` lifetime that `Line::styled` expects, so this should actually work fine with ratatui's API. So `String` converts to `Cow<'static, str>` through the owned variant, which means `Line::from(String)` gives us `Line<'static>` - that's why the styled approach will work. Now I'm setting up the render function to use `Span` with styling applied.\n\nWriting the render function...\n\nFor `render_status`, I need to switch from returning a plain `String` to `Vec<Line<'static>>` so it can carry style information. The good news is that `Paragraph::new()` accepts both formats, so the call site in `draw_ui` won't need to change.\n\nThe tricky part is the tests—they currently check if the rendered output contains certain strings. I could update the tests, but the cleaner approach is to keep `render_status()` returning `String` for backward compatibility and add a separate `render_status_styled()` method that returns the styled lines. That way `draw_ui` uses the styled version while tests continue working unchanged.\n\nFor the worker list, it already returns `Vec<Line<'static>>`, so I just need to add styling to those lines.\n\nNow I'm thinking about the REPL fallback in the `run()` function. I need to check terminal capabilities and either launch the full TUI or fall back to the REPL mode if the terminal doesn't support it. I'm setting up an enum to represent whether the terminal can handle the full TUI or needs to fall back, then checking those capabilities...\n\nChecking terminal capabilities...\n\nI need to verify whether stdout is actually a terminal before proceeding. I'm considering using `crossterm`'s terminal detection since it's more reliable than the standard library approach, though `std::io::IsTerminal` should work fine in Rust 1.70+. Let me go with the crossterm approach for better compatibility.\n\nNow I'm mapping out the full implementation strategy for the TUI changes: I'll add color support detection and terminal capability checking, introduce a theme system with the `Theme` struct, integrate it into `AppState`, then systematically update the rendering functions to apply themed styles throughout the conversation display, worker list, and status lines.\n\nWriting the implementation... the modal hints are already covering most cases. For the acceptance criteria about visible hints, I should add a hint line to the status pane showing the main keyboard shortcuts since that area has room and is always visible. I'll create a method to render this hint line with the key actions formatted clearly.\n\nNow I'm implementing the code changes to tui.rs... Writing the color support infrastructure... Checking terminal capabilities and defining the theme structure...\n\nNow I'm implementing the Theme builder that selects between different color schemes based on the detected color support level, with a default implementation that falls back to no-color mode if needed.\n\nStill writing theme styles... Continuing with the high contrast theme... Defining the no-color style variant...\n\nI'm realizing the `Default` impl needs to call `Self::build()` rather than `Self::default()` to avoid infinite recursion, and I'm using `Self::default_colors()` for the actual defaults instead. Since `Theme` already implements `Default`, I can add it as a field to `AppState` and keep the derive macro since all fields will have default implementations.\n\nFor testing, I need to cover the color detection logic—checking that `NO_COLOR` and `TERM=dumb` disable colors, that the theme builder respects those settings, and that the conversation rendering uses the right markers. The `Style` type does implement `PartialEq`, so I can assert on style fields directly in tests, though testing terminal capabilities will be tricky without a real TTY environment.\n\nNow looking at the acceptance criteria for key hints, I see the current interface has hints scattered across different panels—the worker panel shows Alt+Up/Down and Alt+S, the approval modal lists y/n/a keys, and status lines use text indicators. I should consolidate this by adding a persistent hint line in the status area that displays the main shortcuts like Ctrl+C for quit, Enter to submit, and Shift+Enter for newlines.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1640,"cache_read_input_tokens":62538,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1640},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b35f4001-d232-4171-b853-fb6a26d102e1","uuid":"97eb24b2-55a2-425b-97d0-5d40eb6e5631"}
